iso_retirement.name: Chimakum
iso_retirement.comment:
"Chimakum" is just an alternate spelling for Chemakum, which is the more common
spelling in the linguistic literature. However, since it has been listed with
this spelling in the Ethnologue, it is probably appropriate to include this
alternate spelling in the standard.

The Mimi language as documented by Gaston Decorse in
**hh:hw:Gaudefroy-Demombynes:Oubangui-Chari** is missing from E16/E17/E18/E19/E20/E21/E22/E23/E24. I have never been able to find out where Decorse collected the wordlist and where his informant came from but presumably it was collected somewhere in SE Chad or NE Central African Republic on Decorse's trip in 1902-1904 (**hh:h:Decorse:Congo-Tchad**) and the wordlist shows Arabic and Maban loans (**hh:hv:Starostin:Mimi**), so it was probably also spoken in Wadai. The language has not been sighted for over a century and is therefore likely extinct.

Minkin, a poorly attested extinct language of possible Tangkic affiliation,
is missing from E16/E17/E18/E19/E20/E21/E22/E23/E24 (**hh:hvw:Evans:Minkin**, **hh:w:Coward:Burketown**).

ethnologue_comment.comment: Mure, an extinct Bolivian language of uncertain affiliation attested only with the Pater Noster in **hh:h:Teza:Americane** and a few sporadic mentions (**hh:hv:Hervas:Americanas**:251, **hh:h:Bueno:Obispado-Santa-Cruz**), is missing from E16/E17/E18/E19/E20/E21/E22/E23/E24. It is not to be confused with the more well-known Chapacuran Bolivian language called Moré or Itene [ite] (**hh:g:Angenot-de-Lima:More**). See also: Itene [ite].

ethnologue_comment.comment:
The long extinct and poorly attested Tasmanian languages are missing altogether from E16/E17/E18/E19/E20/E21/E22/E23/E24.  The exact number of languages in evidence is uncertain but a tradition of scholarship
(**hh:hv:Bowern:Tasmanian**, **hh:hb:Jones:Tasmanian**, **hh:hv:CrowleyDixon:Tasmanian**, **hh:hvw:Schmidt:Tasmanischen**, **hh:hv:BowernLau:Tasmanian**)
recognizes some seven languages which may be divided up as Western Coastal Tasmanian, the Northeastern Tasmanian dialect chain, Oyster Bay-Big River-Little Swanport, Port Sorell, South-Eastern Tasmanian Hinterland, Bruny Island and Ben Lomond-Cape Portland,

meds: Conrad, Robert J. and T. Wayne Dye 1975
